* JSON files may contain an array of objects.
* You can iterate through this array and access each object individually using a loop.
* Each object can be accessed using its index in the array.

---

**Example:**

```cpp
#include 
#include 
#include "json.hpp"

using json = nlohmann::json; // Alias for json library
using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Open the JSON file
    ifstream file("data.json");

    // Parse the JSON file into a json object
    json j;
    file >> j;

    // Loop through the array of JSON objects using a standard for loop
    for (int i = 0; i < j.size(); ++i) {
        cout << "Name: " << j[i]["name"] << endl;  // Access the "name" key for each object
        cout << "Age: " << j[i]["age"] << endl;   // Access the "age" key for each object
        cout << "-----" << endl;  // Separator for clarity
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Example `data.json:`**

```json
[
    {
        "name": "John",
        "age": 30
    },
    {
        "name": "Alice",
        "age": 25
    },
    {
        "name": "Bob",
        "age": 22
    }
]
```

